Mobile Phone Usage

What’s going on with this data?

1. Phone Usage Minutes by Emotional Score

This boxplot shows how mobile phone usage minutes vary across different emotional states. Scores in the middle range show high variability, suggesting that emotional neutrality may coincide with a wider range of digital engagement.For example, participants with emotional score 3 (neutral) had usage times ranging from about 150 to over 500 minutes, while those with scores of 1 or 5 tended to cluster around 300–400 minutes.

2. Daily Mobile Phone Usage Trend

This line chart shows the trend in average mobile phone usage over time. A gradual increase can be seen, possibly linked to academic workload or habit formation as the semester progresses. For instance, average usage rose from around 200 minutes in early April to over 340 minutes by mid-May.

3. Sleep Duration vs Phone Usage

This bar chart compares average phone usage across different sleep hour groups. Surprisingly, those with 4–6 and 10+ hours of sleep tend to use phones more than those who sleep very little, indicating that more rest may relate to more engagement.

4. Primary Activity Keyword Frequency

This bar chart presents the frequency of keywords like “Video”, “Social”, and “Study” from phone activity responses. Entertainment and communication dominate the digital activity landscape among the participants. Specifically, “Video”51 times, “Social”39 times, and “Study”40 times, showing how participants divide their phone time.

Conclusion

These visualisations provide insight into how mobile phone habits intersect with emotional wellbeing, rest, and primary tasks. The combination of observational logging and tidy data techniques helps uncover personal digital behavior trends.
